PSA-CAR Special Release: 2015 CAR Population
Highlights of the Cordillera
2015 Census of Population
Total Population
 The latest 2015 Census of Population (POPCEN 2015) results, as proclaimed
by His Excellency President Benigno S. Aquino III under Proclamation No.
1269 dated May 16, 2016, revealed that the total population of Cordillera
Administrative Region (CAR) as of August 1, 2015 was at 1.72 million.
 Cordillera remained the least populated region in the country across census
years. In 2015, CAR only comprised 1.71 percent of the total population of
the Philippines, which is 100.98 million. In 2010, CAR comprised 1.75
percent of the country’s population of 92.34 million. While in 2000, the region
comprised 1.79 percent of the country’s population of 76.51 million.
 Based on the 2010 Census of Population and Housing, the total population of
the region was 1.62 million. This 2015, the total population of CAR increased
by 6.50 percent or additional 105,139 persons.

Total Population of City and Provinces
 The total population of all provinces increased from 2010 to 2015. Benguet
had the highest increase by 10.47 percent or an additional 42,280 persons,
followed by Ifugao with 6.14 percent or an addition of 11,724 persons.
 Mountain Province had the least increase of 403 individuals to the provincial
population count in 2010. This number account for only 0.26 percent
increase.
 Across censuses, Baguio City continued to increase in terms of population.
From 2010 to 2015, there was an increase of 8.38 percent or 26,690 persons.
 Benguet remained to be the most populated province in the region. With a
total population of 446,224, Benguet comprised 25.91 percent of the region’s
total population.
 Abra came in second place as the most populated province with a population
count of 241,160 that comprised 15.34 percent of the total population of the
region.
 Apayao remained to be the least populated province. Apayao registered a
population count of 119,184 that comprised only 6.92 percentage share of
Cordillera’s population.

 Baguio City, which is considered a highly urbanized city, outnumbered all the
provinces except for Benguet. The city’s total population posted at 345,366
that comprised 18.48 percent of CAR’s total population.

Annual Population Growth Rate (APGR)
 CAR population increased by 1.21 percent annually, on average, during the
period 2010 to 2015. By comparison, the rate at which the region’s population
grew during the period 2000 to 2010 was higher at 1.70 percent.
 The APGR of 1.21 means that 1 person was added for every 100 persons in
the population, on average, yearly from 2010 to 2015 and close to 2 persons
yearly from 2000 to 2010.
 Benguet had the highest growth rate at 1.91 percent from 2010 to 2015.
While Mt. Province appeared to have the lowest growth rate at 0.05 percent
from 2010 to 2015.
 From 2000 to 2010, the growth rate of Baguio City was higher than all the
provinces with 2.36 percent annual average growth rate. However, from 2010
to 2015, the city came in next to Benguet in terms of average annual growth
rate that significantly decreased to 1.54 percent.

 The POPCEN 2015 results revealed that Baguio City was the most populated
city among the city/municipalities of CAR. Followed by La Trinidad, Benguet
with a total population of 129,133. City of Tabuk, Kalinga came out third with a
total population of 110,642.
 The bottom three municipalities or the least populated city/municipalities,
came from the province of Abra. They were the municipalities of Daguioman,
Bucloc, and Langiden.
 At the barangay level, Irisan barangay of Baguio City was the most populated
barangay in the region with a total population of 30,507. Pico, La Trinidad
was second with a total population of 23,282. While Bulanao of City of Tabuk,
with a population of 19,636 came out third. The results show a similarity
between the mostly populated Top 3 City/Municipality and Top 3 Barangay.

 The least populated barangays were all from Baguio City. The Bagong
Lipunan or the Market Area only had a population of 28. Malcolm Square-
Perfecto with 31 persons and Kabayanihan barangay with a total population of
116
Technical Notes
Growth rate – the rate at which the population is increasing (or decreasing) in a given period due to
natural increase and net migration, expressed as a percentage of the base population
Total population – refers to the sum of household population and institutional population. Household
population comprises of persons who belong to a household while Institutional population comprises
of persons who are found living in institutional living quarters.
POPCEN 2015 – Census of Population 2015, was undertaken by the Philippine Statistics Authority in
August 2015 pursuant to Republic Act No. 10625, also known as the Philippine Statistical Act of 2013
and Executive Order No. 352 – Designation of Statistical Activities That Will Generate Critical Data for
Decision-Making of the Government and the Private Sector, which stipulates the conduct of a mid-
decade census primarily to update the population count in all barangays nationwide.
